reviewText: As a whole, I would rate the One Piece series as 5 stars.  This particular DVD set I had to go with only 3.  Half of the collection is filler, and pretty weak filler at that (Sanji gives a cooking lesson, Usopp plays with fireworks, Chopper hangs out with Robin, etc.).Still, the other half of the episodes that followed the Manga were pretty decent.  We are finally starting the Skypia Arc, which I am really looking forward to.

reviewText: Collections four and five, which I liked quite a bit, had the all-encompassing arc of the Alabasta fight. As I mentioned in my review for Collection Five, episodes 110 to 126 span the course of a half an hour.  I liked it, but it was kind of exhausting. Also, with one key bad guy that must be stopped, at least one event is predictable.Collection Six is back to smaller arcs. The first episode has Tony Chopper accidently breaking a water barrel, and he has to go refill it. In the meantime, he relates some of his origin. A series of these short, well-written character stories follows.There is plenty of blatant foreshadowing, that I managed to miss completely, until it was explained.  Throughout the collection, the stories and characters are good, and there's never a false note.  The episodes covered are the following.  At some point, it becomes obvious that they'll eventually reach a place called Skypiea, but that's about the only obvious outcome. Bookend episodes are:131. The first patient! The untold story of the rumble ball!156. Already criminals?! Skypiea's upholder of the law!Well-planned, well-written.  These are a bit different than most US TV shows, which start with a few episodes, then maybe get funding for a few more episodes, and then get permission to write and finish a season if the ratings are okay.  Highly recommended.

reviewText: my son absolutely loves the One Piece series and I've bought the entire collection (not the voyages yet though) through Amazon.  However, this particular title did not come with a cardboard sleeve like all 7 of the other collections did.  I was highly disappointed and Cody claims his collection looks stupid without the sleeve.  And yes I returned it once because of this issue only to have another one sent without the sleeve as well.  I even contacted the manufacturer of the DVD and no response.Now that being said, if you enjoy  watching One Piece I do have to say this is a fun collection to own as you can go back and rewatch them over and over - and yes my son has done just that - and I've had to hear all about Luffie's (spelling) adventures.  I admit I'm not a fan but get a real chuckle out of some of the comments I hear coming from the television.

reviewText: The Straw Hat Pirates have made themselves known in Alabasta. By saving the Kingdom from Crockodile. They now have a new crewmember named Robin. They are now trying to find a way to the fabled sky islands. They know for certain that a tresure is there, but is it the One Piece? They outfit their ship to be able to ride the stream up to the sky. It won't be that easy though. There are enemies that will cause trouble and possibly prevent their departure.This anime is incredible. It's got action, comedy, adventure, and suspense. The voice actors are all familiar to just about any casual or serious anime fan. This anime also has a lot of Dragonball-like fun in it. It's tons of fun to watch and keeps you wanting to know what happens next. Now that Funimation has started releasing One Piece in these box sets, it's more affordable than ever. Any fan of anime, or any fan of fun in general will find this series a breath of fresh air. It's a must see.
summary: It's One Piece Again! And It's Still Awesome!
